<div class="explanation">
    <h2>📖 Why Parameterized Queries Work — The Real Reason</h2>

    <div class="explain-grid">

        <div class="explain-card">
            <h3><span class="icon">💀</span> How String Concatenation Fails</h3>
            <p style="margin-bottom:12px">
                When you build a query by gluing strings together, the database
                receives <strong style="color:#f85149">one flat string</strong> and must parse it from scratch.
                It has no idea which parts are your code and which parts came from user input.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Input <code>' OR '1'='1</code> closes your quote, adds new logic</li>
                <li>The DB parser sees a <em>structurally valid</em> new query</li>
                <li>It executes the attacker's intent, not yours</li>
                <li>No amount of regex filtering reliably stops this</li>
                <li>Unicode, encoding tricks, and nested quotes defeat filters</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="explain-card">
            <h3><span class="icon">🛡️</span> How Parameterized Queries Win</h3>
            <p style="margin-bottom:12px">
                A parameterized query sends the <strong style="color:#3fb950">query structure</strong>
                and the <strong style="color:#3fb950">data values</strong> to the database
                as two completely separate things — in two separate protocol messages.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>The DB compiles the query template <em>before</em> it ever sees your data</li>
                <li>Data is bound into pre-defined slots — it <em>cannot</em> change structure</li>
                <li><code>' OR '1'='1</code> becomes a literal string value, not SQL</li>
                <li>The DB will look for a product literally named <code>' OR '1'='1</code></li>
                <li>Works regardless of what characters the input contains</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="explain-grid">

        <div class="explain-card">
            <h3><span class="icon">🔬</span> Step-by-Step: The Vulnerable Path</h3>
            <ol class="step-list">
                <li>User submits: <code>' OR '1'='1</code></li>
                <li>Code builds: <code>SELECT … WHERE name = '' OR '1'='1'</code></li>
                <li>This string is sent to the database engine as-is</li>
                <li>DB parser tokenises it — sees valid SQL with an OR clause</li>
                <li>Condition <code>'1'='1'</code> is always TRUE → all rows returned</li>
                <li>Attacker receives every row including <code>secret_key</code> values</li>
            </ol>
        </div>

        <div class="explain-card">
            <h3><span class="icon">🔬</span> Step-by-Step: The Safe Path</h3>
            <ol class="step-list">
                <li>Code sends template: <code>SELECT … WHERE name = ?</code></li>
                <li>Database compiles and optimises this template immediately</li>
                <li>Structure is now <strong>locked</strong> — cannot be changed</li>
                <li>User input <code>' OR '1'='1</code> is sent as a bound value</li>
                <li>DB treats it as a string literal — looks for that exact name</li>
                <li>No product has that name → zero rows returned. Attack fails.</li>
            </ol>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box">
        <h3>🎯 The Core Insight — Code vs. Data Separation</h3>
        <p>
            SQL injection exists because developers mix <strong style="color:#f85149">code</strong> (the query structure)
            with <strong style="color:#f0883e">data</strong> (user input) in the same string.
            Parameterized queries enforce a hard architectural boundary: the query structure travels
            one way, data travels another. The database engine never re-parses structure after
            receiving data. There is no SQL syntax inside a bound parameter — only a value.
            This is why parameterized queries are a <em>complete</em> fix, not a mitigation.
            Input sanitization is a mitigation (and an incomplete one). Parameterization is a solution.
        </p>
    </div>
