<div class="explain-box">
  <h3>🔍 Why This Works — The Actual Mechanism</h3>
  <div class="explain-grid">
    <div class="explain-item">
      <strong>Vulnerable path: parse-time injection</strong>
      When you concatenate input into a SQL string, the DB engine receives one string and parses it.
      A quote character <code>'</code> closes the string literal context the developer intended.
      Everything after it is parsed as SQL syntax — OR conditions, comments (<code>--</code>),
      UNION clauses, subqueries. The engine has no way to know what was "data" vs "code" because
      by the time it parses, that distinction is gone.
    </div>
    <div class="explain-item">
      <strong>Safe path: separate compilation and binding</strong>
      Parameterized queries send the query template and data in separate protocol messages (or phases).
      The engine compiles the query plan from the template — at that point <code>?</code> or <code>$1</code>
      is a typed placeholder. When the value is bound, it's inserted into the already-compiled plan
      as a scalar value. No re-parsing occurs. A quote in the value is just a character in a string,
      not a syntax token. UNION, OR, <code>--</code> — none of it matters.
    </div>
    <div class="explain-item">
      <strong>Why escaping is not enough</strong>
      Escaping (doubling quotes, backslash-escaping) is encoding, not structural separation.
      It can be bypassed via charset confusion, multi-byte encoding tricks, or developer mistakes
      (forgetting to escape, escaping in the wrong place, second-order injection where escaped
      data is stored then re-used unescaped). Parameterization eliminates the attack surface entirely.
    </div>
    <div class="explain-item">
      <strong>What UNION injection actually does</strong>
      SQL's UNION operator appends rows from a second SELECT to the first result set.
      If column counts and types match, the attacker can read any table they can name.
      Try the "UNION credential dump" preset — the vulnerable mode returns users.password
      in the same result set as product rows. The safe mode ignores the entire payload.
    </div>
  </div>
